Leaf fracture toughness was measured with a pair of scissors (Dovo, Germany) to control and direct crack growth (Lucas & Pereira 1990). The scissors, with an included angle of 55 and a radius of curvature (sharpness) of 1.6 m, were mounted on a portable universal testing machine (Darvell et al. 1996). We fractured leaves in a transverse cut perpendicular to the midrib. This method, described by Lucas et al. (2001), allows the toughness of individual anatomical features, such as the secondary veins and lamina, to be calculated from a single scissors pass.
